2","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England","Martin, Wiltshire, England":"Marten, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Dorset) and Irish (County Mayo): habitational name from Bingham (Nottinghamshire). The placename is probably from an Old English folk-name <i>Bynningas</i> (‘the people associated with a man named <i>Bynna</i>’), or possibly from an unattested Old English word <i>bing</i> ‘a kettle-shaped hollow’, + Old English <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’.","Irish (Ulster, of Scottish origin): altered form of   Bigham  .","American shortened and altered form of various like-sounding Jewish surnames such as   Bingenheimer  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ingham","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Lancashire): habitational name from any of the places called Ingham, particularly in Lincolnshire, Norfolk, and Suffolk. The placename is from the Old English personal name <i>Inga</i> + <i>hām</i> ‘homestead’. In Yorkshire this name was sometimes confused with   Bingham   in the 18th century.","English (of Norman origin): variant of the obsolete Norman surname <i>Engaine</i>; see   Gain  ."]},{"name":"Bigham","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire) and Irish: habitational name from either Bigholm in Beith parish (Ayrshire) or Bigholms in Langholm parish (Dumfriesshire). The second element of the placename is from Older Scots <i>holm</i> (Old Norse <i>holmr</i>) ‘islet’, ‘raised land in a marsh’, ‘a stretch of low-lying land beside a river; a meadow’. The first element may be an unattested Older Scots <i>bigge</i>, a shortened form of <i>bigging</i> ‘building’. The name was taken to Ulster in the 17th and 18th centuries, where it was used interchangeably with   Bingham  ."]},{"name":"Bingenheimer","meanings":["German and Jewish (from Germany): habitational name for someone from Bingenheim on the Eder river (Hesse). Compare   Bingham  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Bingham was born about 1340, in Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England. He died in 1389, in Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England, at the age of 50."},"et":{"Abt 1340–1389":"umbes 1340–1389","1359–Female":"1359–Surnud","1345–Female":"1345–Surnud","1379–Male":"1379–Surnud","1380–Female":"1380–Surnud","1390–1463":"1390–1463","1371–Male":"1371–Surnud","1340–1389":"1340–1389","Abt 1340":"umbes 1340","1359":"1359","1379":"1379","about 1380":"umbes 1380","1389":"1389","1345":"1345","1463":"1463","1340":"1340","1371":"1371","1382":"1382","1380":"1380","1390":"1390","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, 